No. So for instance there is a collision detection algorithm called Gilbert Johnson Keerthi (gjk for short) that uses a minkowski difference to compute a simplex that contains the origin and that simplex would be part of the contact manifold (the full version would come from the expanding polytope algorithm where you would get the penetration normal, depth, and more than just a 4simplex). Another example would be the separating axis theorem where it checks along the 16 unit axes via projection for any separation of the shapes and uses the smallest overlap as the axis along which to push out the contacting objects. So the idea of the contact manifold would be all that kind of information. Is there nothing you can hook a callback function into that the engine will use when it finds two objects touching in the collision detection?

They need to teach Dimensional Analysis from 6th grade onwards. Things make way more sense once you understand that a system built on it's own internal logic needs to make sense within it's own internal logic to function within it's own internal logic. Nothing about physics is "real" in that we don't actually understand the source code of reality. We're looking at arbitrary sections of reality and building models that describe it, like trying to reverse engineer somebody else's computer program only looking at the outputs. Our entire concept of physics has it's own internal logic. Eventually our models hit limitations or gaps, and eventually models are tweaked, integrated, or overturned completely.

AKA The ball doesn't actually accelerate at some arbitrary formula, we have a formula that's sorta accurate at predicting how the ball will move. You're technically correct that the ball might not follow that formula any time you drop it, it's just extremely unlikely. Not ""Quantum chance"" unlikely, I mean ""we had a major oversight in our model on something that's really easy to work out a model for"" unlikely.

The arbitrary soup of units in the middle of A to B working with such formulas is a virtual reality that exists within the internal logic of our model. The Law of Emulation implies it's impossible to work out a system's code within the confines of said system, so no reality formulas for us.
